Comment: Hi everybody!  It was time for Round 5 with Master Freddy and guess what, I lost!  Yup, this furry white kitten has taken another cattermauling.  It is sooo maddening and frustrating.  This time I decided to kick off with a d4 opening and Freddy decided to go Dutch with f5.  I chose what I thought were the best moves from the World DB, i.e. those which would get me a decent piece placement and pawn centre in the middlegame.  Then Freddy took me out of the database with a queen move.  Then Freddy handed my position some hemlock with this queen move.  Later on in the game, after dropping a couple of pawns I tried to break free with a few spite checks and a mate threat but all to no avail - it was only token resistance.

4. Bg2 - pretty standard play against the Dutch - white usually fianchettoes his/her bishop along the h1 - a8 diagonal.  Some nasty pins can occur as a result of this bishop's occupation.  In fact a few moves later I try a double fianchetto, taking a leaf out of Coach Ion's book - remember in our last game he used a double fianchetto against me which proved decisive in his favour!  So why not use it on Master Freddy, eh?

Ba3 - had a good win percentage in the db - it pins the d pawn from taking the e pawn so to avoid being a pawn down black has to recapture with the knight and now an exchange of knights occur on e5.  The downside of this exchange is that it brings out the Wicked Witch of the West onto a good square - she comes with a barreload of hemlock on her broomstick!

45. ............ Rb2  - now I wave the white flag on the grounds of ruinous loss of material because I will drop a rook.  When Henry moves out of the way my h2 rook will be doubly attacked and only once defended (by Henry).  If Rf2 blocking the check then Rxf2, Kxf2, Rxh2  and Freddy will be a whole rook up in a pawn ending.   Back to the drawing board for jstevens1.
